<TEXT>
an opposition party leader has called 
for a plebiscite to decide the sandinista governments future 
erick ramirez head of the nicaraguan social christian party 
proposed a referendum that says no to the continuation of the 
sandinista government and totalitarian project and no to the 
violence and the repression 
ramirez set no specific date for the referendum which he 
proposed while presiding over his partys 31st anniversary 
celebration there was no immediate response to the call from the 
sandinistas 
the opposition party leader also said he might ask the recently 
formed fiveparty coalition the democratic alliance of the 
opposition to condemn sandinista leaders who have driven 
nicaragua to a fatal precipice 
the sandinista national liberation front has ruled nicaragua 
since july 1979 when it overthrew the rightist dictator anastasio 
somoza 
nicaraguas five opposition political parties formed the 
alliance on oct 4 to invigorate the fight of the people using 
civil democratic and patriotic solutions to the severe crisis 
shaking nicaragua 
ramirez on sunday accused the sandinistas of failing to honor 
the esquipulas ii peace accords signed by central american 
countries last year 
they are opportunists who only have sought their own 
wellbeing he said 
just before the alliances formation ramirez announced a 
broad block of civicpolitical opposition with the 
participation of former sandinista eden pastora known by his war 
pseudonym commander zero pastora helped lead the fight against 
somoza 
at that time ramirez defined the new opposition block as the 
third option that would offer different alternatives to the 
radical polarized positions that exist in nicaragua 
the reference was to the leftist sandinista and a usbacked 
rebel band called the contras 
nicaraguan president daniel ortega later responded that 
nicaragua does not have three options you are either with the 
revolution or with the foreign aggressor the sandinista 
president said 
when proposing the plebiscite sunday ramirez said nicaraguas 
opposition parties should be on the offensive and coordinate 
forces in the common fight for national salvation 
the socialchristian leader also said he would continue to fight 
for total amnesty for political prisoners who have been jailed 
in the nine years since the fall of the somoza regime 
