<TEXT>
the rev barry harris admits he 
sometimes gets the itch to play the horses and its a difficult 
urge to avoid working around 1100 of them on the back side at 
fairmount park race track 
harris began ministering to the nomadic peoples on the back 
side the area behind the grandstand where horses train and 
trainers sleep in may 1985 
i had the feeling that some of my brother ministers treated me 
with some suspicion and were a bit cool toward me the southern 
baptist said recalling his start 
just for the simple fact that im here where betting gambling 
takes place i just figured it wasnt my job to judge but to 
minister 
thrice weekly starting at 8 am harris broadcasts an 
economical prayer and devotional message over the 
publicaddress system to the tracks 1500 workers 
he then strolls around to the stables meeting members of the 
horseracing industry including jockeys horse owners and trainers 
the 44yearold harris born in nearby east st louis says 
people seek his counsel for many reasons including problems with 
relationships health or downright boredom 
whatever turns up thats what ill deal with said the 
silverhaired reverend wearing brown leather boots faded blue 
jeans a crisp white shirt a grayblueandbrown tie and a 
creamcolored jacket 
thats where i find out about the wedding thats being 
planned i did one in the winners circle he recalled laughing 
the groom was a jockey 
harris who also works at the track two evenings weekly holds a 
bible study tuesdays in the horsemens lounge on thursdays before 
racing starts he has a devotional service for the jockeys 
he says people who work the back side which at fairmount 
shelters about 1100 horses need a chaplain because their 
migratory life doesnt permit them to put down roots 
theyre a nomadic people he said theyre not plugged 
into the community where they are 
harris said it wasnt that he dreamed of growing up to become a 
track chaplain he never gave it much thought really though his 
father a steel worker traded horses part time 
he graduated from a belleville high school in 1961 got married 
and started working on the railroad then around age 24 in search 
of another career harris entered the ministry 
while serving as pastor at highland southern baptist church 
harris sought to supplement his churchs income to finance a 
building expansion in 1985 the track job came open and he took it 
replacing another southern baptist minister 
the job has existed since 1979 supported by the horsemens 
benevolent and protective association 
i love it here harris said yeah you get the urge every 
once in a while to bet but its not in my game 
he doesnt try to justify the legalized betting at the track 
which southern baptists dont look kindly upon its not there 
for me to approve or disapprove he said its there 
i am not god i cannot stop these things i am here to 
administer to persons 
