the sovietstyle government is 
changing its tactics against moslem guerrillas in the battle for 
power as moscows army withdraws 
the government dominated by a communist party that has been 
trying to portray itself as the real defender of the moslem faith 
is campaigning for international pressure to halt american and 
pakistani support for the guerrillas 
both the soviet union and the afghan government have been 
maneuvering for a negotiated settlement rather than a military 
showdown although moscow continues to arm the kabul government 
the guerrillas have also achieved some changes such as the 
ability to move weapons faster from pakistan to the hills outside 
kabul but they still lack the coordination for a significant new 
strategy 
however some western diplomats believe the fierce afghan winter 
poses less of an obstacle to the guerrillas ability to mount 
attacks on kabul than in the past 
the withdrawal of about 50000 soviet soldiers this summer gave 
the guerrillas greater control of roads and highways especially 
those leading from their supply bases in pakistan to kabul this 
means they are no longer restricted to taking circuitous routes 
through mountains where winter snows often block the passes 
the remaining soviet soldiers estimated at 50000 to 55000 
