<TEXT>
extreme rightwing groups have been turning down 
the volume of loudspeakers used to amplify streetcorner speeches 
out of deference to the ailing emperor tokyo police said today 
its been very quiet lately said an officer with the 
metropolitan police department the rightists seem to be showing 
selfrestraint as the emperor is ill 
emperor hirohito 87 the worlds oldest reigning monarch has 
been bedridden since he vomited blood sept 19 
rightwing groups in japan are notorious for driving through 
major cities in convoys of militarystyle jeeps and trucks blaring 
recorded marching music and anticommunist slogans from public 
address systems 
among the goals of many extreme rightists are revising japans 
constitution to allow the remilitarization of the country and 
reinstating the emperors prewar status as a godlike soveriegn 
lately we have been quieter in our daily campaigning because 
the emperor is ill said a member of the extreme rightist great 
japan patriots party weve turned down the volume of our 
speakers but our leader continues to make his daily speeches 
she refused to divulge her name or the membership of the party 
estimated to be as high as 5000 but said the group has been 
praying daily for the recovery of the emperor 
the metropolitan police officer who requested anonymity added 
that a national meeting of the leftleaning japan teachers union 
sunday opened peacefully with rightists quietly passing out 
handbills the meeting is scheduled to continue through wednesday 
the unions meetings are usually a target for rightist 
groups he said but there has been little trouble the 
officer said 34 rightists demonstrated sunday and only 40 police 
were mobilized no rightists were reported protesting today 
he said that at the unions general meeting in tokyo last year 
nearly 2000 rightists in 400 cars and trucks turned out in 
protest and 1800 riot police were dispatched to keep the peace 
