<TEXT>
while antiabortion activists assaulted 
clinics during last weeks siege of atlanta a lowerkey though 
no less intense battle raged in michigan over a ballot measure 
aimed at outlawing taxfinanced abortions for the poor 
the referendum in michigan one of three states with 
abortionrelated questions on novembers ballot is being closely 
watched because so much money is being spent more than 3 million 
budgeted by both sides 
abortion foes here have passed out lifesavers candies in hopes 
of mobilizing the likeminded without offending anyone else 
the prochoice side is considered the underdog outfinanced and 
outorganized by the antiabortion forces 
michigan is certainly the bellwether state theres no 
question about it said dr john willke president of national 
right to life but im not going to predict any of this i dont 
know whos going to win 
in arkansas where officials say no state funds are used to pay 
for abortions voters nonetheless are being asked to enshrine the 
noabortion spending policy in the state constitution and to 
declare the policy of the state of arkansas is to protect the 
life of every unborn child from conception until birth 
jerry cox executive director of the unborn child amendment 
committee said a victory at the polls would put arkansas in 
position to outlaw all abortions if the us supreme court ever 
modifies roe vs wade the landmark 1973 decision legalizing 
abortion 
in colorado prochoice forces are trying to repeal a 
constitutional amendment similar to arkansas since 1984 medicaid 
abortion spending has been prohibited except in extreme situations 
campaign officials estimate total spending on the ballot 
question could reach 1 million 
the current prohibition against public funding is extreme 
its unfair and its expensive said ed zorensky of colorado 
taxpayers for choice 
according to the state office of budget and planning it would 
cost four times as much in welfare costs to force unwilling women 
to bear unwanted children and support them on welfare than to 
provide public funding for abortion 
prochoice activists there believe they lost the 1984 campaign 
because the ballot wording confused voters 
colorado is a very strong prochoice state if we get the 
message out i think well win zorensky said 
the campaign is hottest in michigan where attention has 
centered on the impact of the committee to end taxfunded 
abortions not with my money you dont advertisements 
i worry about the tremendous amount of resources the other 
side is putting into misleading media said debra ness who 
tracks the state ballot campaigns for the national abortion rights 
action league unless we have the resources to counter those 
messages its not a fair test of the question of choice 
the message from the committee to end taxfunded abortions 
deliberately is not about choice 
its commercials put together by the agency handling george 
bushs presidential campaign advertising feature welldressed 
people talking in a nice restaurant about how theyre going to vote 
the ads make a distinction between the issue of abortion and the 
issue on the ballot 
the way that its framed is very very clever ness said 
money buys sophistication the antis are trying to make their 
stand in michigan 
the state league of women voters which wont choose sides 
between political candidates is working with the prochoice 
coalition and has lambasted the antiabortion campaign claiming it 
is disguising its longterm goals behind the ads 
the peoples campaign for choice a coalition of womens 
religious and labor groups thats fighting to defeat michigans 
proposal a says 6 million a year in welfare abortion spending is 
not the only thing at stake in the campaign 
the group contends that if voters strip the poor of the right to 
a statepaid abortion it will give momentum to those seeking to 
end all abortions 
in atlanta more than 450 people were arrested last week in four 
days of protests dubbed the siege of atlanta by operation 
rescue the new yorkbased antiabortion group that staged the 
demonstrations 
