<TEXT>
a judge today dismissed federal 
hostagetaking charges against indian activist timothy jacobs but 
said he would leave it to a jury to decide whether his fellow 
defendant was guilty on that charge 
four other charges against jacobs still stood 
attorneys for jacobs on friday had argued that prosecutors had 
failed to prove that he and eddie hatcher had made a demand on the 
federal government during their takeover of the robesonian 
newspaper in lumberton on feb 1 
us district court judge terrence boyle said this morning that 
his reading of the statute showed that a demand on the government 
had to be not just incidental but material 
up to 20 people were held hostage in the newspaper office for as 
much as 10 hours while the two defendants demanded an investigation 
into what they said was local corruption and racial discrimination 
no one was injured 
boyle said prosecutors had presented no evidence that jacobs had 
made a demand or had aided hatcher in making a demand to the 
federal government in hatchers case though he said the jury 
should decide the question testimony had indicated that hatcher 
did most of the talking during the incident 
the hostagetaking charge was linked with a second charge of 
committing a violent crime with an illegal firearm boyle also 
dismissed that charge against jacobs 
jacobs still faces charges of conspiracy making an illegal 
firearm possessing an unregistered firearm and conveying false 
information concerning explosives 
in his ruling today boyle also indicated he would not accept a 
necessity defense for the two defendants because there was no 
direct relationship between the hostages taken at the robesonian 
and the threats perceived by the two 
the two defendants had argued that their lives were in jeopardy 
because of information they had allegedly linking law enforcement 
officers to drug trafficking in robeson county they claimed they 
had no choice but to take hostages at the newspaper to publicize 
their case and save their lives 
last week defense attorney lewis pitts had argued for dismissal 
of the hostage charge against jacobs saying that there is 
absolutely no proof as to timmy jacobs making a demand on the 
federal government 
pitts argued that the federal hostagetaking law was designed to 
deal with international seizures and that congress had specifically 
wanted strict limits on its use in domestic cases 
what may have been done may have been conspicuously a crime 
but the question is whether its a criminal matter against the 
united states boyle had said friday 
it appears we have here a situation that the evidence appears 
to show was a locally generated grievance boyle said it arose 
in robeson county and it had to do with matters in robeson county 
the demand on the federal government arose from a demand for 
state action a special prosecutor which state law apparently 
did not allow 
the federal prosecutor assistant us attorney john bruce had 
argued that the federal charges were relevant because the two asked 
to surrender to fbi agents and included in their written list of 
demands a requirement for a federal investigation in robeson county 
