<TEXT>
mississippis oyster season opened monday 
amid dire projections that the 1988 harvest would likely be 
onetwentieth of what it was only five years ago 
gulf coast officials say erratic weather patterns and pollution 
have combined to devastate the local oyster reefs this seasons 
harvest is expected to be fewer than 20000 sacks compared with 
the 365560 sacks taken in 1983 
each year its getting worse and worse said kirk ladner 
whose business terrys seafood in waveland buys oysters from 17 
boats 
ladner said because of the limited oyster population in 
mississippi waters and because the commercial dredging limit has 
been lowered to 10 sacks per day many oystermen will likely head 
for louisiana waters where they can take 30 sacks a day 
however ladner said mississippi oysters are in demand because a 
sack of them produces twice as much meat as a sack of any other 
kind 
marshes once protected oysters in the mississippi sound by 
acting as a natural buffer between salt water and fresh water 
barge canals through marshes and the channelization of rivers and 
bayous has sent flood waters directly into the sound these sudden 
pulses of fresh water kill oysters 
in 1983 flood waters rushed through the bonnet carre spillway 
and into the mississippi sound destroying nearly 4000 acres of 
oyster reefs in 1986 a drought left the sound saltier which made 
conditions ripe for snails called oyster drills to wipe out the 
harvest 
while clam shells have been planted in the mississippi sound 
this year to provide a base for young oysters to grow on many feel 
the salvation of the oyster industry is four years away a proposed 
62 million spillway along the bonnet carre spillway could allow a 
regulated flow of fresh water into the mississippi sound 
if estimates are correct this us army corps of engineers 
project could increase oyster production to 38 million pounds a 
year by restoring the flow of fresh water through the marshes of 
louisiana and into the mississippi sound 
but even with this freshwater regulator droughts floods and 
pollution could continue to kill oysters 
basically i believe youre talking mother nature said john 
cirino a biotechnician at gulf coast research laboratory cirino 
is coordinating the bureau of marine resources bmr shellfish 
program 
in the last 10 years weve had three major floods and three 
years of high salinity and in between three years of good 
production he said 
