<TEXT>
tamil rebels hacked and shot to death 
47 sleeping villagers the military said monday one year after 
indian troops were sent to this island nation to end the violence 
by the insurgents 
indian troops near the village of ulukulama 150 miles northeast 
of the capital ambushed 40 rebels hiding in the jungle after the 
massacre of the villagers killing 12 of the insurgents according 
to the indian high commission in colombo 
the massacre was the worst burst of violence since the indian 
soldiers landed in sri lanka on oct 10 1987 to quell the 
5yearold tamil rebellion for a separate homeland in the 
northeastern part of the island 
in another development in the southern city of matara 85 miles 
south of colombo soldiers opened fire on antigovernment 
demonstrators who attacked a police station according to police 
five people were killed and four wounded also on monday two bombs 
exploded in the suburbs of colombo injuring four people including 
two soldiers police said 
in colombo and most other cities on the island shops and 
businesses remained closed monday in a protest by the majority 
sinhalese population against the governments peace overtures to 
the tamil insurgents 
the government imposed a 48hour curfew monday beginning at 6 
am ordered schools closed in many districts and put security 
personnel on alert 
there were no private vehicles on the roads and 
governmentowned buses were escorted by heavily armed soldiers 
on sunday night about 75 tamil rebels attacked the village of 
ulukulama and killed 47 people including 13 women and 18 children 
said a military official in colombo who demanded anonymity 
at least four people were seriously injured and 11 homes were 
set on fire in the attack said the official he said the victims 
who were sinhalese were either fatally shot or hacked to death 
with knives and swords 
the village massacre occurred on army day which honors sri 
lankan soldiers involved in a drive against the insurgents in april 
1987 on the northern jaffna peninsula 
the sinhalese claim the government is granting too many 
concessions to the tamils including a peace accord signed in july 
1987 to end the civil war that has claimed at least 8500 lives 
under the accord the rebels agreed to surrender their weapons 
in exchange for limited autonomy but they reneged on the plan in 
october 1987 claiming they were not satisfied with the provisions 
for selfrule 
the attack on the village occurred one day before nominations 
for local elections in the province were scheduled to end the 
largest rebel group the liberation tigers of tamil eelam called 
for a boycott but three other insurgent groups have filed 
nominations for seats on the provincial council the date of the 
elections has not been set 
about 47000 indian soldiers were stationed in the islands 
tamildominated northeastern province to put down the rebellion 
india became involved in the ethnic conflict of its southern 
neighbor because of the sympathies of its own 60 mllion tamils for 
the rebel cause 
tamils comprise 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million people and 
claim they are discriminated against by the sinhalese who make up 
75 percent of the population and control sri lankas military and 
government 
the sinhalese peoples liberation front has vowed to kill all 
supporters of the peace plan and has been blamed for at least 500 
killings since the accord was signed 
