down from 122 million members in 1979 to 91 million this summer 
smokestack industries such as that stateowned british steel 
which now is being readied for privatization have shed thousands 
of workers in thatcherordered shakeups 
the manufacturing industry now employs 5 million people 2 
million fewer than in 1979 service industries often 
nonunionized employ 15 million up 200000 
the economy is growing at 4 percent a year faster than most 
other industrialized countries fueled by creditcard buying that 
has sent the trade deficit heading toward 20 billion this year 
four times higher than originally estimated 
but opinion polls indicate that most britons still feel better 
off and doubt the labor party can preserve their prosperity 
twothirds of britons own their homes up from 50 percent when 
mrs thatcher came to power and enabled tenants mostly 
bluecollar to buy statesubsidized houses the laborites 
initially opposed the policy but now espouse it 
kinnock wants to ready labor for the next general election 
probably in 1991 but the conference left question marks over how 
far the party will let him go 
the unions block votes helped kinnock crush a leftwing bid to 
unseat him and adopt the firststage policy reforms these include 
jettisoning commitments to renationalize all stateowned industries 
sold by mrs thatcher and to repeal all her unioncurbing laws 
but the resentments conflicts and class overtones burst through 
when ron todd leader of the powerful 125 millionmember transport 
and general workers union turned against the leadership calling 
it all sharp suits and cordless telephones clipboards and 
scientific samples 
todd a workingclass cockney further embarrassed kinnock by 
using his unions block vote to kill an attempt to water down the 
pledge of unilateral nuclear disarmament 
it illustrated labors main problem the party is funded by the 
unions that founded it in 1900 but the very power the union bosses 
exercise 90 percent of the conference voting strength portrays 
labor as a prisoner of trade union militancy 
todd 61 characterizes an old and shrinking workingclass 
constituency 
kinnock a welsh miners son is a university graduate and at 
46 a generation away from his workingclass origins 
gavin laird moderate leader of the engineers union saw the 
kinnocktodd battle as hastening the day when labor governments 
finally disengage from the unions 
come the day when we have the next labor government there 
will be no tea and cookies at downing street any more he said 
we will have a healthy armslength relationship 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
maureen johnson a correspondent in london for 
the associated press specializes in british politics 
</TEXT>
