<TEXT>
the government does not publish figures on gold production but 
the soviet union is recognized as a world leader shilo who still 
works in the prestigious academy of sciences in moscow estimates 
that perhaps 20 percent of the nations gold comes from the far 
east 
one exploration chief in the area vladimir zinchenko said the 
government buys gold from the mines for 18 rubles a gram a third 
of an ounce on paper that works out to 29 at the official 
exchange rate of the ruble and adds up to more than twice the world 
market price of about 400 an ounce but such figures have little 
meaning because the ruble is not a convertible currency on world 
markets and its black market value is only a fraction of the 
official rate 
but gold itself can buy the goods now unavailable to soviets in 
poorly supplied stateowned stores 
zinchenko said the black market price for gold is about 78 
rubles 125 a gram more than four times the official price 
fifty years ago magadan was little more than a passthrough 
point for the gold fields and labor camps of the kolyma river basin 
a couple of stone houses and rows of wooden barracks resting on 
the hills overlooking the harbor were all that greeted prisoners 
who had endured weeks on crowded filthy eastbound trains to 
vladivostok from there they were loaded on ferries for the 
1350mile trip north to magadan and then sent inland from there 
shilo passed through magadan on his way north in 1938 as did 
asir sandler who was a prisoner 
sandler who said he was accused of spying was on his way as a 
forced laborer in the gold mines where he recently recalled 
prisoners could expect to be overworked underfed and dead within a 
year 
sandler survived however and lives today in magadan as a 
writer 
mayor gennady dorofeyev of magadan said the last of the old 
prison barracks were torn down in 1987 
magadan residents dorofeyev added had discussed turning some 
of them into monuments to the horror of stalins repression but 
decided its better that we build homes and kindergartens instead 
of such gloomy places 
officials insist that economic development and the heavy 
migration to the far east makes it look to the future instead of 
the past 
klyuchnikov the academy of sciences researcher said 
development of the far east must emphasize joint projects by small 
and midsized enterprises with japan china and other pacific 
countries 
officials in magadan said they are eager to work out agreements 
with pacific neighbors including the united states one joint 
fishprocessing agreement already has been set 
vyacheslav kobets government leader of magadan province who 
headed a delegation that visited alaska in september said the 
soviets think there are much greater opportunities for joint 
sovietamerican cooperation in fishing oil exploration and tourism 
we have taken only the first step in our common 
relationship he said 
