threeyearold stephanie rendons world is dark 
and muffled but she and other deafblind children are getting some 
help they need to reach out and take the risks that lead to 
learning 
stephanie already speaks a few words signs about 15 is slowly 
learning how to walk and is being toilet trained all major 
accomplishments for a child born without any hearing or sight 
whose bright mind is difficult to reach 
most with her handicaps remain helpless passive individuals 
unable to do anything but express the most basic needs 
it is difficult to teach profoundly deafblind children 
communication and language so they function far below their 
potential and usually as a retarded individual said cathee m 
christensen a san diego state university associate professor of 
communicative disorders 
christensen runs an experimental program aimed at finding out 
how to motivate deafblind children to learn the us education 
department which is spending 286000 for two years on the 
program serves about 5520 deafblind children and young adults 
