<DOCNO> AP881010-0279 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mci communications corp has agreed to refund 
as much as 33 million to current and former customers who were 
billed for longdistance telephone calls that rang but were 
unanswered 
if approved by a chicago court the agreement will settle 
several classaction lawsuits alleging that mci improperly billed 
customers for longdistance calls that didnt get through 
under the agreement people who were mci customers from 1978 
through 1985 are entitled to a refund or credit of either 21 cents 
for every unanswered call the person can show as having been 
billed or 63 cents for each of the eight years the person was an 
mci customer 
a hearing on approval of the settlement is set for next jan 5 
in cook county circuit court in illinois details of the agreement 
were made public last week 
billing for unanswered calls was a problem for other 
longdistance companies as well us sprint communications co 
settled a similar lawsuit in july 1987 agreeing to pay customers 
as much as 48 million spokesman syd courson said 
the problems date to the early days of longdistance competition 
when new competitors generally got connections with local phone 
companies that were inferior to those used by american telephone amp 
telegraph co 
this unequal access caused a number of problems including 
insufficient and sometimes false electronic signals that determine 
whether a call has been answered some companies considered calls 
that rang more than a certain number of times or for a certain 
length of time to have been answered and the customer was billed 
for the call 
now with about 85 percent of the regional bell phone companies 
lines converted to offer comparable connections to all 
longdistance companies the problem of unanswered calls has been 
nearly eliminated mci said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

